The stores are my primary interest — Apple’s firsthand purchase data for
millions of customers. It’s a touted feature that if a user downloads an audio
track or app they’re free to download it again at no cost. Users don’t need to
worry about switching hardware or reinstalling; no concerns over paying again
or losing data.

I’ve been wondering what would happen if Apple took things a step further and
bound OS Ⅹ user accounts to Apple IDs. What if you could log into any Mac and
have access to your applications and personal data? Or be able to access your
own information on anyone’s iOS device?

* * *

The central issue with such an idea is the user’s data. Apple already offers
cloud storage and synchronization through its MobileMe service — currently a
minimum of 20 <abbr class="smallcaps" title="gigabytes">GB</abbr> for
<abbr class="smallcaps" title="United States dollars">USD</abbr>$99 per year.

  [mobileme]: http://www.apple.com/mobileme/ "Apple’s MobileMe page"
  [mobilemeprice]: http://www.apple.com/mobileme/pricing/ "MobileMe pricing overview"

It doesn’t offer full syncing, though; instead, users can choose to sync
data from certain Apple applications, and can use the remaining space allowance
to store data in [iDisk][idisk]. This approach of selective syncing isn’t
enough for a truly portable experience. As
<span class="person">Shawn Blanc</span> [discusses][blanc], Apple should follow
the example of [Dropbox][dropbox] and synchronize anything the user wants.
